2. DIFFICULTY ESCALATION (200%):

   * The difficulty must be AT LEAST 200% higher than the hardest CBSE board question.
   * The questions should psychologically feel closer to JEE Advanced
     while remaining syllabus-legal.
   * A student must struggle NOT because of calculation,
     but because of:
     • Strategy selection
     • Logical sequencing
     • Hidden constraints
     • Multi-layer reasoning

3. ZERO DIRECTNESS:

   * NEVER ask direct questions like:
     • “Find”
     • “Prove”
     • “Calculate”
     • “Show that”
   * The question must NOT reveal:
     • Which formula to use
     • Which concept to apply
     • Even whether the problem is numerical or logical
   * The student must first figure out:
     WHAT is happening
     BEFORE figuring out
     HOW to solve it.

4. MULTI-ANGLE THINKING (MANDATORY):

   * Each question must require at least TWO or MORE of the following:
     • Reverse reasoning
     • Constraint-based elimination
     • Case analysis
     • Counterfactual (“What if this condition was altered?”)
     • Logical contradiction
     • Inference from incomplete data
     • Pattern recognition
   * Single-path questions are NOT allowed.

5. NO SIMILARITY — ZERO TOLERANCE:

   * NO two questions may:
     • Look similar
     • Use the same logical structure
     • Be solved using the same mental approach
   * Each question must train a DIFFERENT mode of thinking.
   * Imagine each question attacks the brain from a new direction.

6. CONCEPT FUSION (WITHIN CHAPTER):

   * Every question must combine MULTIPLE sub-concepts
     from DIFFERENT parts of the SAME chapter.
   * Simple, isolated concept testing is NOT allowed.

7. THINKING BEFORE MATH:

   * Computation must be secondary.
   * The real challenge must be:
     • Deciding assumptions
     • Identifying variables
     • Structuring the solution
   * Even a strong calculator should NOT help without thinking.

8. ELITE STUDENT FILTER:

   * These questions should meaningfully challenge
     the TOP 1% of Class 10 students.
   * A normal “good student” should feel lost.
   * A top student should feel challenged but intrigued.

9. QUESTION STYLES (USE VARIETY):
   Use a strategic mix of:

   * Hidden-assumption problems
   * Assertion–reason (non-obvious)
   * Logical paradox-style questions
   * Multi-case decision problems
   * Reverse-result problems
   * “Impossible unless…” problems
   * Constraint-satisfaction problems

10. NO SOLUTIONS:

    * Do NOT provide hints.
    * Do NOT provide steps.
    * Do NOT provide answers.
    * Only QUESTIONS.

